{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d2d43523-a75a-4d28-8a6d-559606f6f795","content":"# Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the MCP Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that:\n\n1. **Spawns your server** as a child process using stdio\n2. **Lists tools/resources** — click \"List Tools\" to verify registration\n3. **Lets you invoke tools** — select a tool, fill in parameters, and see the JSON response\n4. **Shows raw protocol messages** — useful for debugging serialization issues\n\n### Tips\n\n- If your server needs environment variables, pass them with `--env`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector --env KEY=VALUE dotnet run --project ./YourServer.csproj\n  ```\n- Use `--args` if you need to separate inspector flags from your server's arguments.\n- Ensure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC only to **stdout** — any logging should go to **stderr**, otherwise the inspector can't parse the protocol frames.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da3f30fb-e8db-4f16-ba1f-8635c0c15fec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling - I can answer this directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":336,"requestId":"201D:23A6C6:1618ECE:18C5756:6A0521BC"},"id":"6803216f-7b64-40c3-a021-3562699a4591","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:13:41.373Z","parentId":"4b397115-43b7-41f1-bc70-6ac5bb4e648a"}
